{"cursor":"2248","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Chowdhury ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|ÚÙØ¯ÙØ±Ù}}}}; {{lang-bn|à¦à§à¦§à§à¦°à§}}; {{lang-hi|à¤à¥à¤§à¤°à¥\n}})' is a term in Indo-Aryan languages, literally meaning \"holder of four\".\nChowdhury (also spellt Choudhury, Chaudhari, Chaudhary, Choudhury, Chaudhury,\nChaudhry, Choudhury, Chowdhery, Chaudhary, or Choudhry) is a hereditary title of\nhonour, awarded by Mughal Emperors to persons of eminence. Traditionally, the\nterm is used as a title indicating the ownership of ancestral land, but in\ncontemporary usage it is often taken as a surname or title. They may be regarded\nas de facto land barons in rural landscape.\n\nDuring the Mughal era, a talukh or district usually consisted of 84 villages and\na central town. The Talukhdar was required to collect taxes, maintain law and\norder, and provide military supplies and manpower to the provincial government.\nIn most cases the Talukhdar's were entitled to retain 10% of the collected\nrevenue. . Caste such as Arain ,Mian, Mehar are also called as Chaudhry\n\nHowever, during the Sikh rule in Punjab this title became very common and quite\na few village headmen or \"Lumberdars\" were given \"Chowdhary\" as a title by\nMaharaja Ranjit Singh. Ever since, the Chowdharys of Chakwal style themselves\nas \"Chowdharial\" to distinguish themselves from the newly appointed\nmen. In northern Indian states such as Haryana, Punjab, Rajasthan,\nBihar and Uttar Pradesh, the title is used by landowning ethnic group and\ncommunities like Gujjars Jatt, Tyagi and Maithil Brahmin, in Pakistan Jatts and\nGujjarss use this title.\n","linknr":130,"url":"chaudhuri","recorded":1364183828,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Chaudhary&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Chaudhary&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-s